> Can you tell me a recipe for an excellent apple-pear tart (I have Granny Smiths and Bosc, for an adult discrimination of taste), with a pecan crust?
**assistant**:
> Certainly, here's a recipe for an apple-pear tart with a pecan crust that should satisfy adult taste buds. This recipe will serve about 8 people.
> 
> ## **Ingredients**
> 
> #### **For the Crust:**
> 
> - 1.5 cups of pecans
> - 1 cup of all-purpose flour
> - 2 tablespoons of sugar
> - 1/2 teaspoon of salt
> - 1/2 cup (1 stick) of cold unsalted butter, cut into small pieces
> - 2 tablespoons of ice water
> 
> #### **For the Filling:**
> 
> - 3 tablespoons of unsalted butter
> - 2 Granny Smith apples, peeled, cored and sliced thinly
> - 2 Bosc pears, peeled, cored and sliced thinly
> - 1/4 cup of sugar
> - 1 teaspoon of ground cinnamon
> - 1/2 teaspoon of ground nutmeg
> - 2 teaspoons of lemon juice
> 
> #### **For the Glaze:**
> 
> - 2 tablespoons of apricot jam or honey
> - 1 tablespoon of water
> 
> ## **Instructions**
> 
> **For the Crust:**
> 
> 1. Preheat oven to 375 degrees Fahrenheit (190 degrees Celsius).
> 2. In a food processor, pulse pecans, flour, sugar, and salt until the mixture resembles coarse meal. Add cold butter and pulse until mixture looks like wet sand. Add water and pulse until the dough comes together.
> 3. Press dough evenly into the bottom and up the side of a 9-inch tart pan. Freeze until firm for about 15 minutes.
> 4. Bake until crust is golden brown, 20 to 25 minutes. Let it cool.
> 
> **For the Filling:**
> 
> 5. While the crust is freezing and baking, prepare the filling. In a large skillet, melt the butter over medium heat.
> 6. Add the apples and pears to the skillet and sprinkle with sugar, cinnamon, nutmeg, and lemon juice
> 7. Cook, stirring often, until the apples and pears are just softened and released their juice, about 10 minutes.
> 8. Let the cooked fruit mixture cool slightly, then spread in the baked tart shell.
> 
> **For the Glaze:**
> 
> 9. In a small saucepan, over low heat, melt the apricot jam or honey with water, stirring until it has a glaze-like consistency.
> 10. Brush the glaze over the cooled apple-pear mixture.
> 
> Let the tart cool for a few minutes before serving. You can enhance the flavor with a scoop of vanilla ice cream or a dollop of whipped cream on top.
> 
> Enjoy your apple-pear tart with a pecan crust!
